  "texts": [
    "These covariates help enrich the data and, in some cases, reveal hidden relationships between hydrocarbon distribution and the covariates themselves.",
    "Various models incorporate such auxiliary information with varying levels of interpretability, from krig-ing with external drift (De Fouquet, 2006), to machine learning approaches (Meng et al., 2023).",
    "Spatially Varying Coefficients (SVC) has regained recent interest (Comber et al., 2024; Finley and Banerjee, 2020; Mu et al., 2018), as it offers a nice middle ground between the two worlds, by letting the relationships between dependent and independent variables vary across space, it offers great flexibility and at the same time retains all the interpretability (Finley, 2011).",
    "The most common methods for modeling such data are the Geographically Weighted Regression (GWR) (Fotheringham et al., 2009) and Gaussian Process SVC (GP-SVC) (Dambon et al., 2021).",
    "The GP-SVC model, which assumes that the coefficients follow Gaussian processes, provides a rigorous approach to account for spatial non-stationarity."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
